<DOC><DOCNO> AP880926-0221 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-88 1546EDT</FILEID><FIRST>s i BC-Chile-Glance ADV02   09-26 0423</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Chile-Glance, ADV 02,0430</SECOND><NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE><HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Chile-at-a-Glance</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: one of a four-story package</NOTE><HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD><TEXT>   Here are some facts and figures on Chile:      THE LAND _ Chile is a long, narrow territory of 292,000 squaremiles extending 2,670 miles along the southwestern coast of SouthAmerica. It ranges from the semi-tropical, desert north to therainy, windswept south. Wedged between the Andes mountains on theeast and Pacific Ocean on the west, its average width is only 95miles. Its largest cities are Santiago, the capital, where nearly 5million of the nation's 12 million people live; Valparaiso, itslargest port, 75 miles north west of Santiago, and Concepcion, anindustrial center 350 miles south. It is bordered by Peru on thenorth and Bolivia and Argentina on the east.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE PEOPLE _ The population is predominantly a mixture of thelocal Araucano Indians and descendants of the Spanish conquerors.In the agricultural southern provinces a large German immigrantcommunity exists. The official language is Spanish, and literacyexceeds 90 percent. While Chile has no official religion, more than90 percent of Chileans call themselves Roman Catholics.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE ECONOMY _ Chile is the world's second biggest producer ofcopper, after the United States. In recent years, the economy hasdiversified and the country has become the Southern Hemisphere'slargest fruit exporter. Mining, fishing and agriculture, includinga booming timber industry, are the main economic activities. Theannual economic growth rate has averaged 5 percent since themid-1980s. Inflation stands at around 10 percent annually, one ofthe lowest rates in Latin America. The currency is the peso, andthe present exchange rate is 246 pesos to the U.S. dollar.</TEXT><TEXT>   HISTORY _ Chile launched a struggle for independence from Spainon Sept. 18, 1810, and finally attained it in 1818, becoming arepublic and establishing a reputation as one of Latin America'smost stable democracies. Presidents were freely elected, even in1881 during a victorious four-year territorial war againstneighboring Bolivia and Peru. Major political disturbances werehistorically rare, consisting of a brief civil war in 1891 and aseries of coups in 1925. In 1973, however, the military led by Gen.Augusto Pinochet ousted the elected leftist government of PresidentSalvador Allende, an avowed Marxist who died in the takeover.Pinochet has remained in power since and seeks ratification of anew period of rule, until 1997, in an Oct. 5 referendum.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 2</NOTE></DOC>